pr_body:
This PR contains a "Cartesian Grid" option in the UI Menu, that opens a mat-menu, that has some options to customize a cartesian grid, such as:
- Show Cartesian Grid
- Show Labels (i.e. coordinates on the axes)
- Show XY Planes
- Change the number of XY Planes
- Show YZ Planes
- Change the number of YZ Planes
- Show ZX Planes
- Change the number of ZX Planes
- Change sparsity of the gridlines
Update tests for the cartesian grid. Created a draft request, after which I will finalise the changes.

pr_title: Add a functionality to show 3d points and distance, and to translate cartesian grid
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 1307591057, 'comment_body': "I don't really understand what this is supposed to do? When I click on it, then I get very weird behaviour - the grid jumps around and I cannot work out what it is intersecting. Also, once this is enabled, how do you disable it? The checkbox never seems to be ticked.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 8, 28, 15, 39, 33, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'EdwardMoyse', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1307665932, 'comment_body': 'Actually, I made the grid translatable, by two methods, one, by value, another, by pointer.

1. By value, I can set the values of x, y, z of the new origin of the grid, and upon clicking "save", it will shift the grid to the new origin.
2. By Pointer, I need to click on "shift cartesian grid", and then, on clicking at any point, and grid will be translated there. The closest intersect under the mouse pointer will decide the origin.

On clicking "shift Cartesian Grid", the user can keep clicking to shift the grid, but to stop it, he needs to right-click (as suggested by @kjvbrt ). Now, the grid will no longer move and stay on its new origin. This explains the unchecking of the "shift cartesian grid" checkbox.

Changing the origin of the grid also changes the origin of everything. So, if I change the origin to say, (100, 100, 100), then if I enable "show 3d points", and click on a point, say "100, 0, 0", then its coordinates will be shown as "0, -100, -100".', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 8, 28, 16, 40, 16, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Somya-Bansal159', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1308311585, 'comment_body': 'Okay, but if it's right click to disable, then I don't think
1.  this should be a checkbox
2. you should add some text to the dialog to explain what is going on.
3. it would be nice if the x,y,z numbers in the dialog updated when you click 

I'm also not sure about changing where we report 3d points. Maybe as a compromise you could show both, if the grid origin is no longer 0,0,0?
i.e. if the grid is at the origin, just print the current message, and if not something like "Absolute coordinates are (100,0,0) and (0,-100,0) compared to grid"', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 8, 29, 7, 11, 58, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'EdwardMoyse', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1309065389, 'comment_body': 'I made the suggested changes, could you please review it, and as well, trigger the CI/CD?', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2023, 8, 29, 16, 11, 53, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'Somya-Bansal159', 'type': 'User'}]

pr_title: Add a functionality to highlight subdetectors
pr_body:
This feature is similar to collections info, except that, it works for detector geometries.

The highlight feature is working as expected.

But as for the "move camera to object", I am a bit unsure, what it would seem like to zoom into the big detector geometries. As of now, I am zooming into the origin of the geometries, and then zooming out by (1000, 1000, 1000).

Can you suggest any suitable icon for it?

Also, in the "collections info", the highlight feature didn't seem to be working properly. I tried to fix that as well, by setting effectsManager antialiasing to false, whenever we need to highlight an object.
